[49m[39m    1,   1[0m:[39m[49m # Recipe 14.5: Operating Room Block Scheduling
[0m[49m[39m    2,   2[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    3,   3[0m:[39m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Production · **Estimated Cost:** ~$200-800/month (solver compute)
[0m[49m[39m    4,   4[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    5,   5[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m    6,   6[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    7,   7[0m:[39m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[39m    8,   8[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m    9,   9[0m:[39m[49m Every Monday morning, the OR scheduling office is a war room. Orthopedics wants more block time because their cases keep bumping into the afternoon. Cardiothoracic is furious because their allocated blocks sit empty on Thursdays (their surgeons are in clinic). General surgery says they can fill any open slot but never gets allocated enough. The chief of surgery wants overall utilization above 75%. The CFO wants contribution margin maximized. The nurses want predictable shift patterns. Everyone has a spreadsheet proving they deserve more time.
[0m[49m[39m   10,  10[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   11,  11[0m:[39m[49m Operating room block scheduling is the process of allocating fixed time blocks (typically half-day or full-day segments) to surgical services or individual surgeons on a repeating weekly or monthly template. Each OR in a hospital might have 10-12 blocks per week. A 20-OR hospital has 200+ blocks to assign. The allocation determines who gets access to the most expensive real estate in the hospital.
[0m[49m[39m   12,  12[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   13,  13[0m:[39m[49m Here's why this is such a painful problem: ORs cost $30-100 per minute to operate (depending on the facility), and they sit idle roughly 20-30% of scheduled time at most hospitals. That's millions of dollars evaporating annually because the block schedule doesn't match actual demand. Meanwhile, surgeons with insufficient block time are sending cases to competitors. Under-allocated services create access bottlenecks for patients. Over-allocated services produce empty rooms that still require staffed teams on standby.
[0m[49m[39m   14,  14[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   15,  15[0m:[39m[49m The traditional approach is a committee meeting every 6-12 months where department chairs negotiate block allocations based on historical volume, political leverage, and how loudly they complain. The result is a schedule that's outdated by the time it's implemented, unfair in ways nobody can articulate precisely, and resistant to change because any adjustment creates a loser.
[0m[49m[39m   16,  16[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   17,  17[0m:[39m[49m This is a mathematical optimization problem pretending to be a political one. Let's make it a mathematical one for real.
[0m[49m[39m   18,  18[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   19,  19[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m   20,  20[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   21,  21[0m:[39m[49m ## The Technology: Constrained Optimization for Resource Allocation
[0m[49m[39m   22,  22[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   23,  23[0m:[39m[49m ### What Is Block Scheduling Optimization?
[0m[49m[39m   24,  24[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   25,  25[0m:[39m[49m At its core, block scheduling is a resource allocation problem. You have a fixed supply of resources (OR rooms multiplied by time blocks) and competing demand from multiple services. Each allocation decision has downstream consequences: staffing requirements, equipment availability, patient access, and financial performance. The goal is to find an allocation that satisfies a set of hard constraints (things that must be true) while optimizing one or more objectives (things we want to maximize or minimize).
[0m[49m[39m   26,  26[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   27,  27[0m:[39m[49m This is the domain of operations research, specifically mixed-integer programming (MIP) and constraint programming (CP). These aren't machine learning techniques. They're mathematical optimization methods that have been solving logistics, scheduling, and allocation problems for decades. Airlines use them to assign crews to flights. Factories use them to schedule production runs. Hospitals should be using them for OR scheduling, but most still rely on spreadsheets and committee meetings.
[0m[49m[39m   28,  28[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   29,  29[0m:[39m[49m ### The Mathematical Formulation
[0m[49m[39m   30,  30[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   31,  31[0m:[39m[49m Let's get concrete about what we're optimizing. The decision variables are binary: does service S get block B in room R? Yes or no. That gives us a three-dimensional assignment matrix.
[0m[49m[39m   32,  32[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   33,  33[0m:[39m[49m **Decision variables:**
[0m[49m[39m   34,  34[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   35,  35[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m   36,  36[0m:[39m[49m x[s, r, b] = 1 if service s is assigned to room r in block b
[0m[49m[39m   37,  37[0m:[39m[49m              0 otherwise
[0m[49m[39m   38,  38[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   39,  39[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   40,  40[0m:[39m[49m **Hard constraints** (must be satisfied, no exceptions):
[0m[49m[39m   41,  41[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   42,  42[0m:[39m[49m - Each block in each room is assigned to at most one service
[0m[49m[39m   43,  43[0m:[39m[49m - Each service gets at least its minimum guaranteed blocks (contractual obligations)
[0m[49m[39m   44,  44[0m:[39m[49m - No service exceeds its maximum capacity (staffing limits)
[0m[49m[39m   45,  45[0m:[39m[49m - Equipment-heavy specialties (cardiac, neuro) only go in equipped rooms
[0m[49m[39m   46,  46[0m:[39m[49m - Certain services cannot be adjacent (infection control: orthopedic implants and general contaminated cases in the same room on the same day is a problem)
[0m[49m[39m   47,  47[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   48,  48[0m:[39m[49m **Soft constraints** (preferences, weighted in the objective):
[0m[49m[39m   49,  49[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   50,  50[0m:[39m[49m - Services prefer consistent rooms (familiarity, equipment setup)
[0m[49m[39m   51,  51[0m:[39m[49m - Surgeons prefer specific days (aligned with clinic schedules)
[0m[49m[39m   52,  52[0m:[39m[49m - Back-to-back blocks for the same service reduce turnover time
[0m[49m[39m   53,  53[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   54,  54[0m:[39m[49m **Objective function** (what we're maximizing):
[0m[49m[39m   55,  55[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   56,  56[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m   57,  57[0m:[39m[49m maximize: w1 * predicted_utilization + w2 * access_score + w3 * contribution_margin - w4 * changeover_penalty
[0m[49m[39m   58,  58[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   59,  59[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   60,  60[0m:[39m[49m Where the weights (w1, w2, w3, w4) represent institutional priorities. A hospital focused on throughput weights utilization heavily. One focused on revenue weights contribution margin. These weights are the policy decisions that leadership makes; the optimizer finds the best schedule given those priorities.
[0m[49m[39m   61,  61[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   62,  62[0m:[39m[49m ### Why This Is Hard
[0m[49m[39m   63,  63[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   64,  64[0m:[39m[49m The naive approach (try all possible allocations, pick the best one) is computationally impossible. With 20 rooms, 10 blocks per room, and 15 services, you have 15^200 possible assignments. That's more combinations than atoms in the universe. Brute force is not an option.
[0m[49m[39m   65,  65[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   66,  66[0m:[39m[49m Modern solvers handle this through branch-and-bound algorithms: they systematically explore the solution space while pruning branches that can't lead to better solutions than the best one found so far. A good formulation (tight constraints, strong relaxations) makes the solver converge in seconds or minutes. A bad formulation can run for hours without finding a provably optimal solution.
[0m[49m[39m   67,  67[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   68,  68[0m:[39m[49m The other hard part isn't mathematical. It's data. To predict utilization, you need historical case volumes by service, case duration distributions, cancellation rates, and seasonality patterns. Garbage data produces a "mathematically optimal" schedule that performs terribly in practice.
[0m[49m[39m   69,  69[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   70,  70[0m:[39m[49m ### Solver Selection
[0m[49m[39m   71,  71[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   72,  72[0m:[39m[49m There are two main families of solvers for this kind of problem:
[0m[49m[39m   73,  73[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   74,  74[0m:[39m[49m **Mixed-Integer Programming (MIP) solvers:** Gurobi, CPLEX, COIN-OR CBC, HiGHS. These handle linear and quadratic objectives with integer variables. They provide optimality guarantees (you know how close to optimal your solution is). Commercial solvers (Gurobi, CPLEX) are dramatically faster than open-source alternatives for large problems, but the open-source options (CBC, HiGHS) work fine for most hospital-scale instances.
[0m[49m[39m   75,  75[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   76,  76[0m:[39m[49m **Constraint Programming (CP) solvers:** Google OR-Tools CP-SAT, IBM CP Optimizer. These excel at feasibility problems (finding any solution that satisfies all constraints) and scheduling problems with complex temporal relationships. CP-SAT is particularly good for scheduling and is free.
[0m[49m[39m   77,  77[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   78,  78[0m:[39m[49m For OR block scheduling, MIP is usually the better fit because the objective function is naturally linear (weighted sum of utilization, revenue, access scores) and the constraints are mostly linear inequalities. CP shines more for the daily case sequencing problem (Recipe 14.7) where temporal ordering matters.
[0m[49m[39m   79,  79[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   80,  80[0m:[39m[49m ### Batch vs. Real-Time Optimization
[0m[49m[39m   81,  81[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   82,  82[0m:[39m[49m Block scheduling is fundamentally a batch problem. You're generating a template that repeats weekly or monthly, then adjusting it periodically (quarterly, or when triggered by utilization reviews). The optimization runs once, produces a schedule, and humans review and approve it.
[0m[49m[39m   83,  83[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   84,  84[0m:[39m[49m But there's a real-time component: block release. When a surgeon doesn't fill their allocated block by a release deadline (typically 72 hours before the slot), the block becomes available to other services. Optimizing which service gets the released block requires a faster, simpler decision that runs on-demand. This is a much smaller optimization (one block, many candidates) and can use greedy heuristics or a simplified model.
[0m[49m[39m   85,  85[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   86,  86[0m:[39m[49m The architecture needs to handle both: a heavyweight batch solver for quarterly schedule generation, and a lightweight real-time engine for daily block release decisions.
[0m[49m[39m   87,  87[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   88,  88[0m:[39m[49m ### General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[39m   89,  89[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   90,  90[0m:[39m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[39m   91,  91[0m:[39m[49m [Historical Data] → [Demand Forecasting] → [Constraint Builder] → [Solver] → [Schedule Output]
[0m[49m[39m   92,  92[0m:[39m[49m                                                                        ↑
[0m[49m[39m   93,  93[0m:[39m[49m                                                                [Policy Weights]
[0m[49m[39m   94,  94[0m:[39m[49m                                                                [Room Constraints]
[0m[49m[39m   95,  95[0m:[39m[49m                                                                [Service Minimums]
[0m[49m[39m   96,  96[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m   97,  97[0m:[39m[49m [Real-time Events] → [Block Release Engine] → [Assignment Decision]
[0m[49m[39m   98,  98[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m   99,  99[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  100, 100[0m:[39m[49m The batch path: historical surgical volume, case duration data, and cancellation rates feed a demand forecasting module. Those forecasts, combined with institutional constraints and policy weights, feed the solver. The solver produces a proposed block template. A human reviews and approves it.
[0m[49m[39m  101, 101[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  102, 102[0m:[39m[49m The real-time path: when a block is released (surgeon didn't fill it by deadline), a lightweight engine evaluates candidates and assigns the released time. This might use the same model with fewer variables, or a simpler rule-based approach.
[0m[49m[39m  103, 103[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  104, 104[0m:[39m[49m ---
[0m[49m[39m  105, 105[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  106, 106[0m:[39m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[39m  107, 107[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  108, 108[0m:[39m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[39m  109, 109[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  110, 110[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Lambda for the block release engine.** Released blocks trigger an event-driven decision. The lightweight optimization (one block, score candidates, assign) runs in seconds. Lambda's stateless, event-driven model fits perfectly. No idle compute between release events.
[0m[49m[39m  111, 111[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  112, 112[0m:[39m[49m **AWS Batch for the quarterly solver.** The full block schedule optimization is compute-intensive (a 20-OR hospital with complex constraints might run 5-30 minutes on a powerful machine). AWS Batch lets you spin up the right-sized compute (high-memory, multi-core) for the solver run, then terminate it. You're paying for 30 minutes of compute per quarter, not a perpetually running server.
[0m[49m[39m  113, 113[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  114, 114[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon S3 for data staging and results.** Historical case data, demand forecasts, constraint definitions, and generated schedules all live in S3. The solver reads inputs from S3 and writes results back. This keeps the data layer decoupled from compute.
[0m[49m[39m  115, 115[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  116, 116[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for operational state.** Current block assignments, release status, and real-time availability need fast point lookups. DynamoDB serves this operational layer with single-digit millisecond reads.
[0m[49m[39m  117, 117[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 118     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for demand forecasting.** Predicting future case volumes per service requires time-series forecasting. SageMaker hosts the trained forecasting models that feed utilization predictions into the optimizer. (The forecasting model itself is built with techniques from Chapter 12.)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for demand forecasting.** Predicting future case volumes per service requires time-series forecasting. SageMaker hosts the trained forecasting models that feed utilization predictions into the optimizer. (The forecasting model itself is built with techniques from Chapter 12.) For quarterly-only forecasting, consider SageMaker Serverless Inference or batch transform jobs instead of a persistent endpoint, which reduces cost to ~$10-30/month.
[0m[49m[39m  119, 119[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  120, 120[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for scheduling triggers.** The quarterly optimization run, daily block release checks, and utilization monitoring all happen on schedules or in response to events. EventBridge orchestrates the timing.
[0m[49m[39m  121, 121[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  122, 122[0m:[39m[49m **Amazon QuickSight for schedule visualization.** Decision-makers need to see the proposed schedule, compare it to current allocation, and understand the predicted impact. QuickSight dashboards present utilization heatmaps, service allocation summaries, and what-if comparisons.
[0m[49m[39m  123, 123[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  124, 124[0m:[39m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[39m  125, 125[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  126, 126[0m:[39m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[39m  127, 127[0m:[39m[49m flowchart TB
[0m[49m[39m  128, 128[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Data Layer
[0m[49m[39m  129, 129[0m:[39m[49m         A[S3: Historical Cases] --> B[SageMaker: Demand Forecast]
[0m[49m[39m  130, 130[0m:[39m[49m         C[S3: Constraints & Weights] --> D[Constraint Builder Lambda]
[0m[49m[39m  131, 131[0m:[39m[49m         B --> D
[0m[49m[39m  132, 132[0m:[39m[49m     end
[0m[49m[39m  133, 133[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  134, 134[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Batch Optimization
[0m[49m[39m  135, 135[0m:[39m[49m         D -->|Model File| E[AWS Batch: MIP Solver]
[0m[49m[39m  136, 136[0m:[39m[49m         E -->|Solution| F[S3: Proposed Schedule]
[0m[49m[39m  137, 137[0m:[39m[49m         F --> G[QuickSight: Review Dashboard]
[0m[49m[39m  138, 138[0m:[39m[49m     end
[0m[49m[39m  139, 139[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  140, 140[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Real-Time Release
[0m[49m[39m  141, 141[0m:[39m[49m         H[EventBridge: Release Deadline] --> I[Lambda: Release Check]
[0m[49m[39m  142, 142[0m:[39m[49m         I -->|Unfilled Blocks| J[Lambda: Release Optimizer]
[0m[49m[39m  143, 143[0m:[39m[49m         K[DynamoDB: Current Assignments] --> J
[0m[49m[39m  144, 144[0m:[39m[49m         J -->|Assignment| K
[0m[49m[39m  145, 145[0m:[39m[49m     end
[0m[49m[39m  146, 146[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  147, 147[0m:[39m[49m     subgraph Operations
[0m[49m[39m  148, 148[0m:[39m[49m         G -->|Approved| K
[0m[49m[39m  149, 149[0m:[39m[49m         K --> L[API Gateway: Schedule API]
[0m[49m[39m  150, 150[0m:[39m[49m         L --> M[EHR / Scheduling System]
[0m[49m[39m  151, 151[0m:[39m[49m     end
[0m[49m[39m  152, 152[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  153, 153[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  154, 154[0m:[39m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[39m  155, 155[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  156, 156[0m:[39m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[39m  157, 157[0m:[39m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[39m  158, 158[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Services** | AWS Batch, Lambda, S3, DynamoDB, SageMaker, EventBridge, API Gateway, QuickSight |
[0m[49m[39m  159, 159[0m:[39m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `batch:SubmitJob`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `events:PutRule` |
[0m[49m[39m  160, 160[0m:[39m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (schedule data may reference surgeon names and service lines; if linked to patient data for utilization analysis, PHI applies) |
[0m[49m[39m  161, 161[0m:[39m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest; all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 162     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda and Batch in VPC with endpoints for S3, DynamoDB |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda and Batch in private subnets. VPC endpoints required: S3 (gateway), DynamoDB (gateway), SageMaker Runtime (interface), EventBridge (interface), CloudWatch Logs (interface), ECR API + DKR (interface, for Batch image pull), KMS (interface), STS (interface). Budget ~$50-70/month for interface endpoints in a 3-AZ deployment. If using a commercial solver with license validation, add a restricted NAT route for the license server CIDR only. |
[0m[49m[39m  163, 163[0m:[39m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: audit all schedule modifications for compliance and dispute resolution |
[0m[49m[39m  164, 164[0m:[39m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic surgical case logs. OR benchmarking collaboratives publish anonymized utilization data. Never use real surgeon names in dev environments. |
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 165     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Batch solver: ~$2-5 per run (30 min on c5.4xlarge quarterly). Lambda: negligible. DynamoDB: ~$25/month. SageMaker endpoint: ~$100-400/month depending on forecast complexity. Total: $200-800/month. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Batch solver: ~$2-5 per run (30 min on c5.4xlarge quarterly). Lambda: negligible. DynamoDB: ~$25/month. SageMaker endpoint: ~$100-400/month (persistent) or ~$10-30/month (serverless/batch transform for quarterly-only). VPC endpoints: ~$50-70/month. Total: $200-800/month. |
[0m[49m[39m  166, 166[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  167, 167[0m:[39m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[39m  168, 168[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  169, 169[0m:[39m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[39m  170, 170[0m:[39m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[39m  171, 171[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Batch** | Runs the heavyweight MIP solver for quarterly schedule generation |
[0m[49m[39m  172, 172[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Builds constraint models, handles block release decisions, orchestration |
[0m[49m[39m  173, 173[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores historical data, constraint files, solver inputs/outputs |
[0m[49m[39m  174, 174[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Operational store for current block assignments and real-time state |
[0m[49m[39m  175, 175[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts demand forecasting models for utilization prediction |
[0m[49m[39m  176, 176[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Triggers quarterly runs, daily release checks, utilization alerts |
[0m[49m[39m  177, 177[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon API Gateway** | Exposes schedule data to EHR and scheduling systems |
[0m[49m[39m  178, 178[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon QuickSight** | Visualization dashboards for schedule review and approval |
[0m[49m[39m  179, 179[0m:[39m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Encryption key management for data at rest |
[0m[49m[39m  180, 180[0m:[39m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Monitoring solver performance, Lambda errors, utilization metrics |
[0m[49m[39m  181, 181[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  182, 182[0m:[39m[49m ### Code (Pseudocode Walkthrough)
[0m[49m[39m  183, 183[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  184, 184[0m:[39m[49m **Step 1: Extract historical demand data.** Before the optimizer can propose a schedule, it needs to understand what each service actually does with its OR time. This step pulls surgical case history (typically 12-24 months) and computes per-service metrics: average weekly case volume, case duration distributions, cancellation rates, and utilization of currently allocated blocks. These metrics become the demand forecast inputs and the baseline against which the new schedule will be measured. Skip this step and the optimizer is flying blind, producing allocations based on nothing.
[0m[49m[39m  185, 185[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Note: for the demand forecast, you need per-service aggregate metrics (weekly volume, duration distributions, cancellation rates), not individual case records. If your data lake stores case-level records, aggregate at query time and don't persist patient-level data in the optimization pipeline's S3 bucket. If case-level data is needed for duration distribution analysis, apply de-identification (remove patient identifiers, generalize dates to week-level) before storing in the optimization pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  186, 188[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  187, 189[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION extract_demand_data(start_date, end_date):
[0m[49m[39m  188, 190[0m:[39m[49m     // Pull all completed surgical cases from the data lake for the analysis window.
[0m[49m[39m  189, 191[0m:[39m[49m     // Each case has: service, room, date, scheduled_duration, actual_duration, was_cancelled
[0m[49m[39m  190, 192[0m:[39m[49m     cases = query S3 data lake for surgical cases between start_date and end_date
[0m[49m[39m  191, 193[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  192, 194[0m:[39m[49m     // Group cases by service to compute per-service demand profiles
[0m[49m[39m  193, 195[0m:[39m[49m     service_profiles = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  194, 196[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  195, 197[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service in distinct services from cases:
[0m[49m[39m  196, 198[0m:[39m[49m         service_cases = filter cases where service matches
[0m[49m[39m  197, 199[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  198, 200[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute weekly volume: how many cases does this service actually do?
[0m[49m[39m  199, 201[0m:[39m[49m         weekly_volumes = group service_cases by ISO week, count per week
[0m[49m[39m  200, 202[0m:[39m[49m         avg_weekly_volume = mean(weekly_volumes)
[0m[49m[39m  201, 203[0m:[39m[49m         volume_std_dev = standard_deviation(weekly_volumes)
[0m[49m[39m  202, 204[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  203, 205[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute duration distribution: how long do their cases actually take?
[0m[49m[39m  204, 206[0m:[39m[49m         // This drives utilization predictions for block allocations.
[0m[49m[39m  205, 207[0m:[39m[49m         durations = extract actual_duration from service_cases
[0m[49m[39m  206, 208[0m:[39m[49m         duration_percentiles = compute p25, p50, p75, p90 of durations
[0m[49m[39m  207, 209[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  208, 210[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute cancellation rate: what fraction of scheduled cases don't happen?
[0m[49m[39m  209, 211[0m:[39m[49m         // High cancellation rates mean allocated blocks sit emptier than expected.
[0m[49m[39m  210, 212[0m:[39m[49m         cancellation_rate = count cancelled cases / count all scheduled cases
[0m[49m[39m  211, 213[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  212, 214[0m:[39m[49m         // Compute current utilization: how well are they using their existing blocks?
[0m[49m[39m  213, 215[0m:[39m[49m         // utilization = actual case minutes / allocated block minutes
[0m[49m[39m  214, 216[0m:[39m[49m         current_utilization = sum(actual_duration) / sum(allocated_block_minutes)
[0m[49m[39m  215, 217[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  216, 218[0m:[39m[49m         service_profiles[service] = {
[0m[49m[39m  217, 219[0m:[39m[49m             avg_weekly_volume: avg_weekly_volume,
[0m[49m[39m  218, 220[0m:[39m[49m             volume_std_dev: volume_std_dev,
[0m[49m[39m  219, 221[0m:[39m[49m             duration_percentiles: duration_percentiles,
[0m[49m[39m  220, 222[0m:[39m[49m             cancellation_rate: cancellation_rate,
[0m[49m[39m  221, 223[0m:[39m[49m             current_utilization: current_utilization
[0m[49m[39m  222, 224[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  223, 225[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  224, 226[0m:[39m[49m     // Store profiles to S3 for the constraint builder to consume
[0m[49m[39m  225, 227[0m:[39m[49m     write service_profiles to S3 as JSON
[0m[49m[39m  226, 228[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  227, 229[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN service_profiles
[0m[49m[39m  228, 230[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  229, 231[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  230, 232[0m:[39m[49m **Step 2: Build the optimization model.** This is the heart of the system. We translate institutional constraints and objectives into a mathematical model the solver can process. The output is a model file (typically in MPS or LP format) that encodes every hard constraint, soft constraint, and the weighted objective function. The constraint builder reads service demand profiles, room capabilities, policy weights, and contractual minimums, then generates the full model. This step is where domain expertise lives: every quirky hospital rule ("ortho can't follow general in Room 4 because the laminar flow hood takes 45 minutes to recalibrate") becomes a constraint.
[0m[49m[39m  231, 233[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  232, 234[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  233, 235[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION build_optimization_model(service_profiles, room_config, policy_weights):
[0m[49m[39m  234, 236[0m:[39m[49m     // Initialize the model. We're building a Mixed-Integer Program.
[0m[49m[39m  235, 237[0m:[39m[49m     model = create new MIP model
[0m[49m[39m  236, 238[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  237, 239[0m:[39m[49m     // Define decision variables: x[service, room, block] = 1 if assigned, 0 otherwise
[0m[49m[39m  238, 240[0m:[39m[49m     // blocks are half-day slots: Monday AM, Monday PM, Tuesday AM, etc.
[0m[49m[39m  239, 241[0m:[39m[49m     rooms = room_config.rooms          // e.g., ["OR-1", "OR-2", ..., "OR-20"]
[0m[49m[39m  240, 242[0m:[39m[49m     blocks = room_config.time_blocks   // e.g., ["Mon-AM", "Mon-PM", "Tue-AM", ...]
[0m[49m[39m  241, 243[0m:[39m[49m     services = keys of service_profiles
[0m[49m[39m  242, 244[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  243, 245[0m:[39m[49m     x = create binary variables x[s, r, b] for all s in services, r in rooms, b in blocks
[0m[49m[39m  244, 246[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  245, 247[0m:[39m[49m     // HARD CONSTRAINT 1: Each block assigned to at most one service
[0m[49m[39m  246, 248[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each room r, each block b:
[0m[49m[39m  247, 249[0m:[39m[49m         add constraint: sum(x[s, r, b] for all s) <= 1
[0m[49m[39m  248, 250[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  249, 251[0m:[39m[49m     // HARD CONSTRAINT 2: Minimum block guarantees (contractual)
[0m[49m[39m  250, 252[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service s:
[0m[49m[39m  251, 253[0m:[39m[49m         min_blocks = get minimum guaranteed blocks for service s from policy
[0m[49m[39m  252, 254[0m:[39m[49m         add constraint: sum(x[s, r, b] for all r, b) >= min_blocks
[0m[49m[39m  253, 255[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  254, 256[0m:[39m[49m     // HARD CONSTRAINT 3: Maximum blocks (staffing capacity)
[0m[49m[39m  255, 257[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service s:
[0m[49m[39m  256, 258[0m:[39m[49m         max_blocks = get maximum feasible blocks for service s (based on surgeon FTEs)
[0m[49m[39m  257, 259[0m:[39m[49m         add constraint: sum(x[s, r, b] for all r, b) <= max_blocks
[0m[49m[39m  258, 260[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  259, 261[0m:[39m[49m     // HARD CONSTRAINT 4: Room capability matching
[0m[49m[39m  260, 262[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service s, each room r:
[0m[49m[39m  261, 263[0m:[39m[49m         IF service s requires equipment not available in room r:
[0m[49m[39m  262, 264[0m:[39m[49m             FOR each block b:
[0m[49m[39m  263, 265[0m:[39m[49m                 add constraint: x[s, r, b] = 0  // service cannot use this room
[0m[49m[39m  264, 266[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  265, 267[0m:[39m[49m     // SOFT OBJECTIVE: Weighted combination of goals
[0m[49m[39m  266, 268[0m:[39m[49m     // Term 1: Predicted utilization (higher is better)
[0m[49m[39m  267, 269[0m:[39m[49m     utilization_score = sum over all (s, r, b):
[0m[49m[39m  268, 270[0m:[39m[49m         x[s, r, b] * predicted_utilization(s, duration_percentiles, block_length)
[0m[49m[39m  269, 271[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  270, 272[0m:[39m[49m     // Term 2: Service access score (meeting demand, higher is better)
[0m[49m[39m  271, 273[0m:[39m[49m     access_score = sum over all s:
[0m[49m[39m  272, 274[0m:[39m[49m         (allocated_blocks[s] / needed_blocks[s]) weighted by priority
[0m[49m[39m  273, 275[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  274, 276[0m:[39m[49m     // Term 3: Room consistency bonus (same service, same room across days)
[0m[49m[39m  275, 277[0m:[39m[49m     consistency_bonus = sum over all (s, r):
[0m[49m[39m  276, 278[0m:[39m[49m         bonus if service s is in room r for multiple blocks in the week
[0m[49m[39m  277, 279[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  278, 280[0m:[39m[49m     // Term 4: Changeover penalty (different services in same room on same day)
[0m[49m[39m  279, 281[0m:[39m[49m     changeover_penalty = sum over all (r, day):
[0m[49m[39m  280, 282[0m:[39m[49m         penalty if AM and PM services differ in room r on that day
[0m[49m[39m  281, 283[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  282, 284[0m:[39m[49m     // Combine into objective
[0m[49m[39m  283, 285[0m:[39m[49m     objective = (policy_weights.utilization * utilization_score
[0m[49m[39m  284, 286[0m:[39m[49m                + policy_weights.access * access_score
[0m[49m[39m  285, 287[0m:[39m[49m                + policy_weights.consistency * consistency_bonus
[0m[49m[39m  286, 288[0m:[39m[49m                - policy_weights.changeover * changeover_penalty)
[0m[49m[39m  287, 289[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  288, 290[0m:[39m[49m     model.set_objective(maximize, objective)
[0m[49m[39m  289, 291[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  290, 292[0m:[39m[49m     // Export model to standard format for the solver
[0m[49m[39m  291, 293[0m:[39m[49m     model_file = model.export_to_mps_format()
[0m[49m[39m  292, 294[0m:[39m[49m     write model_file to S3
[0m[49m[39m  293, 295[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  294, 296[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN model_file_path
[0m[49m[39m  295, 297[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  296, 298[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  297, 299[0m:[39m[49m **Step 3: Run the solver.** The model file goes to a compute environment with a MIP solver installed. For hospital-scale problems (15-30 services, 10-25 rooms, 10-14 blocks per room), commercial solvers like Gurobi typically find a near-optimal solution in 2-15 minutes. Open-source alternatives (HiGHS, CBC) may take 10-60 minutes for the same problem. The solver returns the optimal assignment matrix plus metadata about solution quality (optimality gap, solve time). If the gap is larger than acceptable (say, > 5%), you either need to give the solver more time or tighten your formulation.
[0m[49m[39m  298, 300[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review A1 (HIGH). Add granular solver outcome handling: distinguish infeasible model (relax constraints), suboptimal-but-acceptable solution (gap 5-15%, flag for review but proceed), no feasible solution found (alert ops, don't auto-replace current schedule), and solver crash. Current pseudocode only raises a generic error on failure. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  299, 303[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  300, 304[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION run_solver(model_file_path, time_limit_seconds):
[0m[49m[39m  301, 305[0m:[39m[49m     // Submit the solver job to AWS Batch.
[0m[49m[39m  302, 306[0m:[39m[49m     // The compute environment has the solver binary installed (e.g., HiGHS or Gurobi).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store the solver image in Amazon ECR with image scanning enabled.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Pin to a digest (not :latest) for reproducibility and security.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Scope the Batch job's IAM role narrowly: read from model input prefix, write to solution output prefix.
[0m[49m[39m  303, 310[0m:[39m[49m     job = submit AWS Batch job:
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 304     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m         container_image: "solver-image:latest"   // contains solver + Python bindings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         container_image: "123456789.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/solver@sha256:abc123..."
[0m[49m[39m  305, 312[0m:[39m[49m         command: ["solve", model_file_path, "--time-limit", time_limit_seconds]
[0m[49m[39m  306, 313[0m:[39m[49m         compute: c5.4xlarge (16 vCPU, 32 GB RAM)
[0m[49m[39m  307, 314[0m:[39m[49m         timeout: time_limit_seconds + 300        // buffer for startup/teardown
[0m[49m[39m  308, 315[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  309, 316[0m:[39m[49m     // Wait for job completion
[0m[49m[39m  310, 317[0m:[39m[49m     wait for job to reach SUCCEEDED or FAILED state
[0m[49m[39m  311, 318[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  312, 319[0m:[39m[49m     IF job.status == FAILED:
[0m[49m[39m  313, 320[0m:[39m[49m         raise error "Solver failed. Check logs for infeasibility or resource limits."
[0m[49m[39m  314, 321[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  315, 322[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse the solution from the solver output
[0m[49m[39m  316, 323[0m:[39m[49m     solution = read solution file from S3 (written by the solver container)
[0m[49m[39m  317, 324[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  318, 325[0m:[39m[49m     // Extract key quality metrics
[0m[49m[39m  319, 326[0m:[39m[49m     objective_value = solution.objective_value
[0m[49m[39m  320, 327[0m:[39m[49m     optimality_gap = solution.mip_gap       // how far from provably optimal (0% = perfect)
[0m[49m[39m  321, 328[0m:[39m[49m     solve_time = solution.solve_time_seconds
[0m[49m[39m  322, 329[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  323, 330[0m:[39m[49m     // Parse the assignment matrix back into a human-readable schedule
[0m[49m[39m  324, 331[0m:[39m[49m     schedule = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  325, 332[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each variable x[s, r, b] in solution where value == 1:
[0m[49m[39m  326, 333[0m:[39m[49m         schedule[room r][block b] = service s
[0m[49m[39m  327, 334[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  328, 335[0m:[39m[49m     // Store the parsed schedule
[0m[49m[39m  329, 336[0m:[39m[49m     write schedule to S3 as JSON
[0m[49m[39m  330, 337[0m:[39m[49m     write solution metadata (gap, time, objective) to S3
[0m[49m[39m  331, 338[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  332, 339[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN schedule, optimality_gap
[0m[49m[39m  333, 340[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  334, 341[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  335, 342[0m:[39m[49m **Step 4: Evaluate and compare the proposed schedule.** A raw optimization output is not useful to decision-makers without context. This step computes predicted performance metrics for the proposed schedule and compares them against the current schedule. It answers the questions leadership will ask: "How does utilization change? Which services gain or lose blocks? What's the predicted revenue impact?" Without this comparison, the optimization output is a black box that nobody will trust enough to approve.
[0m[49m[39m  336, 343[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  337, 344[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  338, 345[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION evaluate_schedule(proposed_schedule, current_schedule, service_profiles):
[0m[49m[39m  339, 346[0m:[39m[49m     // Compute predicted utilization per room per block for proposed schedule
[0m[49m[39m  340, 347[0m:[39m[49m     proposed_metrics = empty map
[0m[49m[39m  341, 348[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each room r, block b, assigned service s in proposed_schedule:
[0m[49m[39m  342, 349[0m:[39m[49m         predicted_util = estimate_utilization(
[0m[49m[39m  343, 350[0m:[39m[49m             service_profiles[s].avg_weekly_volume,
[0m[49m[39m  344, 351[0m:[39m[49m             service_profiles[s].duration_percentiles,
[0m[49m[39m  345, 352[0m:[39m[49m             service_profiles[s].cancellation_rate,
[0m[49m[39m  346, 353[0m:[39m[49m             block_duration_minutes
[0m[49m[39m  347, 354[0m:[39m[49m         )
[0m[49m[39m  348, 355[0m:[39m[49m         proposed_metrics[r][b] = {
[0m[49m[39m  349, 356[0m:[39m[49m             service: s,
[0m[49m[39m  350, 357[0m:[39m[49m             predicted_utilization: predicted_util
[0m[49m[39m  351, 358[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  352, 359[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  353, 360[0m:[39m[49m     // Aggregate metrics for comparison
[0m[49m[39m  354, 361[0m:[39m[49m     comparison = {
[0m[49m[39m  355, 362[0m:[39m[49m         overall_utilization: {
[0m[49m[39m  356, 363[0m:[39m[49m             current: mean utilization across all current blocks,
[0m[49m[39m  357, 364[0m:[39m[49m             proposed: mean utilization across all proposed blocks,
[0m[49m[39m  358, 365[0m:[39m[49m             change: proposed - current
[0m[49m[39m  359, 366[0m:[39m[49m         },
[0m[49m[39m  360, 367[0m:[39m[49m         per_service_blocks: {},
[0m[49m[39m  361, 368[0m:[39m[49m         revenue_impact_estimate: 0
[0m[49m[39m  362, 369[0m:[39m[49m     }
[0m[49m[39m  363, 370[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  364, 371[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service s:
[0m[49m[39m  365, 372[0m:[39m[49m         current_blocks = count blocks assigned to s in current_schedule
[0m[49m[39m  366, 373[0m:[39m[49m         proposed_blocks = count blocks assigned to s in proposed_schedule
[0m[49m[39m  367, 374[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  368, 375[0m:[39m[49m         comparison.per_service_blocks[s] = {
[0m[49m[39m  369, 376[0m:[39m[49m             current: current_blocks,
[0m[49m[39m  370, 377[0m:[39m[49m             proposed: proposed_blocks,
[0m[49m[39m  371, 378[0m:[39m[49m             change: proposed_blocks - current_blocks
[0m[49m[39m  372, 379[0m:[39m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  373, 380[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  374, 381[0m:[39m[49m     // Estimate revenue impact from utilization improvement
[0m[49m[39m  375, 382[0m:[39m[49m     // Average OR contribution margin * additional utilized minutes
[0m[49m[39m  376, 383[0m:[39m[49m     additional_utilized_minutes = (comparison.overall_utilization.change
[0m[49m[39m  377, 384[0m:[39m[49m                                    * total_block_minutes_per_week)
[0m[49m[39m  378, 385[0m:[39m[49m     comparison.revenue_impact_estimate = additional_utilized_minutes * avg_contribution_per_minute
[0m[49m[39m  379, 386[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  380, 387[0m:[39m[49m     // Write comparison report
[0m[49m[39m  381, 388[0m:[39m[49m     write comparison to S3 as JSON
[0m[49m[39m  382, 389[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  383, 390[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN comparison
[0m[49m[39m  384, 391[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  385, 392[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  386, 393[0m:[39m[49m **Step 5: Handle block release decisions.** This is the real-time component. When a block release deadline passes (typically 72 hours before the block) and the assigned service hasn't filled the time, the block becomes available. This step scores candidate services for the released block and assigns it to the best match. It's a much simpler optimization than the quarterly schedule generation: one block, multiple candidates, score and assign. Speed matters here because released blocks need to be visible to other services immediately.
[0m[49m[39m  387, 394[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Important: use DynamoDB conditional writes (ConditionExpression ensuring the block is still in "released" state) to prevent double-assignment when multiple blocks release simultaneously. Consider serializing release decisions via Step Functions or a single-concurrency Lambda if concurrent releases are common.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  388, 397[0m:[39m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[39m  389, 398[0m:[39m[49m FUNCTION handle_block_release(room, block, releasing_service):
[0m[49m[39m  390, 399[0m:[39m[49m     // Fetch current demand signals: which services have cases waiting for OR time?
[0m[49m[39m  391, 400[0m:[39m[49m     waitlist = query scheduling system for pending cases without assigned OR time
[0m[49m[39m  392, 401[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  393, 402[0m:[39m[49m     // Score each candidate service for this released block
[0m[49m[39m  394, 403[0m:[39m[49m     candidates = empty list
[0m[49m[39m  395, 404[0m:[39m[49m     FOR each service s with pending cases on the waitlist:
[0m[49m[39m  396, 405[0m:[39m[49m         IF service s can use this room (equipment check):
[0m[49m[39m  397, 406[0m:[39m[49m             score = compute_release_score(
[0m[49m[39m  398, 407[0m:[39m[49m                 cases_waiting: count of pending cases for service s,
[0m[49m[39m  399, 408[0m:[39m[49m                 average_case_revenue: contribution margin for service s cases,
[0m[49m[39m  400, 409[0m:[39m[49m                 time_since_last_block: days since service s last had a released block,
[0m[49m[39m  401, 410[0m:[39m[49m                 utilization_history: service s historical utilization rate
[0m[49m[39m  402, 411[0m:[39m[49m             )
[0m[49m[39m  403, 412[0m:[39m[49m             append {service: s, score: score} to candidates
[0m[49m[39m  404, 413[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  405, 414[0m:[39m[49m     // Sort by score, assign to highest
[0m[49m[39m  406, 415[0m:[39m[49m     sort candidates by score descending
[0m[49m[39m  407, 416[0m:[39m[49m     winner = candidates[0]
[0m[49m[39m  408, 417[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;9m- 409     [0m:[38;5;9m[49m     // Update the operational database
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Update the operational database with conditional write to prevent race conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Also store the full candidate list and scores for audit purposes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Service chiefs will ask "Why did orthopedics get that block and not us?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // You need to answer that question with data for every single release decision.
[0m[49m[39m  410, 422[0m:[39m[49m     update DynamoDB:
[0m[49m[39m  411, 423[0m:[39m[49m         key = {room: room, block: block}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         condition = block_status == "released"   // prevents double-assignment
[0m[49m[39m  412, 425[0m:[39m[49m         set assigned_service = winner.service
[0m[49m[39m  413, 426[0m:[39m[49m         set assignment_type = "released"
[0m[49m[39m  414, 427[0m:[39m[49m         set released_from = releasing_service
[0m[49m[39m  415, 428[0m:[39m[49m         set assigned_at = current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         set decision_audit = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             candidates: candidates,              // full list with scores
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             scoring_version: "v2.1",             // scoring function version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             decided_at: current timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[39m  416, 434[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  417, 435[0m:[39m[49m     // Notify the winning service's scheduling coordinator
[0m[49m[39m  418, 436[0m:[39m[49m     send notification to winner.service coordinator:
[0m[49m[39m  419, 437[0m:[39m[49m         "Block released: {room} on {block_date}. Assigned to {winner.service}."
[0m[49m[39m  420, 438[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  421, 439[0m:[39m[49m     RETURN winner
[0m[49m[39m  422, 440[0m:[39m[49m ```
[0m[49m[39m  423, 441[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): Expert review S1 (HIGH). Add schedule approval access control model: API Gateway endpoint for approval actions authenticated via Cognito/IAM with role-based access (surgical governance committee only). DynamoDB should store schedule state transitions (proposed, under_review, approved, active) with approver identity and timestamp. CloudTrail captures approval events. The approval path should be a first-class architectural element given the politically sensitive nature of schedule changes. -->
